{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"df19f6fcc41202dc5fdea0eeae918830569d40e4e4facf82aa6570b046a610f0","slug":"pages.m04-measures-of-spread-1-of-5","location":"/pages/026-m04-measures-of-spread-1-of-5.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Measures of Spread (1 of 5)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"thumbnail":"/build/spread1-3726fa713d81378c9353ae7820deb9da.gif","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"026-m04-measures-of-spread-1-of-5.md","url":"/build/026-m04-measures-of--c6f1ad697ba9980c161a60f48a56022c.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"kbTwFqNQ81"}],"key":"Jdw6CLMYkE"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Relate measures of center and spread to the shape of the distribution, and choose the appropriate measures in different contexts.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"t3ObXwbuHA"}],"key":"RETTBdqKJM"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Introduction","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"w5oLf66Jjl"}],"identifier":"introduction","label":"Introduction","html_id":"introduction","implicit":true,"key":"OAOGsBD29N"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So far we have learned about different ways to quantify the center of a distribution. A measure of center by itself is not enough, though, to describe a distribution. Consider the following two distributions of exam scores. Both distributions are centered at 70 (the median of both distributions is approximately 70), but the distributions are quite different. The first distribution has a much larger variability in scores compared to the second one.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"v2NMMdksVW"}],"key":"SyyRis4gYQ"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/spread1-3726fa713d81378c9353ae7820deb9da.gif","alt":"Two dot plots of exam scores. The first plot has a median of approximately 70, but there are scores from below 50 to above 90. In the second dot plot, the median is once again about 70, but this time the range of scores is from about 60 to about 80.","key":"Dgdn2GQdvH","urlSource":"images/spread1.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Two dot plots of exam scores. The first plot has a median of approximately 70, but there are scores from below 50 to above 90. In the second dot plot, the median is once again about 70, but this time the range of scores is from about 60 to about 80.","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"AQnVdL6O8z"}],"key":"P1RRsHGD8S"}],"key":"ddySBw1IT7"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"Iu73FH2z92"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In order to describe the distribution, we therefore need to supplement the graphical display not only with a measure of center, but also with a measure of the variability (or spread) of the distribution.","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"Ry4bRUOInM"}],"key":"mswuSItuIb"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In this section, we will discuss the three most commonly used measures of spread:","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"wOOzuG7hNo"}],"key":"GJM2Sz6nYK"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Range","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"key":"OyecO1gbC2"}],"key":"NZbrmJuXmu"}],"key":"byJYx4sqGo"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Inter-quartile range (IQR)","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"Vfxb3OQS4A"}],"key":"IW6AnCNcTX"}],"key":"AJkdnxqgKF"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Standard deviation","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"dFdhNPMT2D"}],"key":"amkCyirUzL"}],"key":"Aw7AlCjpCZ"}],"key":"YC0Vvn9vTc"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Like the different measures of center, these measures provide different ways to quantify the variability of the distribution.","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"key":"dbuc41fpBR"}],"key":"Rf3EW40wVP"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Range","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"JWtmmglEfH"}],"identifier":"range","label":"Range","html_id":"range","implicit":true,"key":"x9K79SgFhr"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The ","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"BxbwYW7WYa"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"range","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"VmFgxMzLvB"}],"key":"ZauOhv9HXF"},{"type":"text","value":" covered by the data is the most intuitive measure of variability. The range is exactly the distance between the smallest data point (min) and the largest one (Max).","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"eJPe3hzuCU"}],"key":"dK1oyZKOMP"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Range = Max - min","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"key":"MkKThG4HND"}],"key":"uIZdA4usfC"}],"key":"egxvKP7E78"}],"key":"D41Us8gT00"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note: When we first looked at the histogram, and tried to get a first feel for the spread of the data, we were actually ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"jBx5KMrH8Z"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","va